	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Shrugging off criticism, European fleets will keep trawling deep seas</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 January 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The Council of European Fisheries Ministers has said that there will be little change in deep-sea quotas for the next two years. In a victory for the French and Spanish fleets, deep-sea fishing will continue largely as before, despite strong objections from conservation organisations and warnings from the international community. The International Council for the Exploration of the Sea (ICES), an organisation of scientists from 200 institutes, recommended that the deep-sea fishing catches ‘be reduced from recent levels even for stocks that are stable’. The United Nations General Assembly called upon governments in March 2010 to immediately put in place guidelines through regional fisheries-management organisations ‘for sustainably managing deep-sea fisheries and protecting vulnerable marine ecosystems.’ A British study published in September 2010 found that bottom-trawling commercial fishing fleets have a more negative impact on the sea floor than all other major human activities combined.</p><p>To date these pronouncements have had little impact on the European fisheries discussions. The European Commissioner for maritime affairs and fisheries was sceptical about such criticism: ‘As regards deep-sea stocks, scientific advice is not always very clear, so it is time to extend the application of the precautionary principle gradually to all stocks’. Earlier this month, she had fought for the backing of European ministers to reduce the bluefin tuna quotas negotiated by the ICCAT, but was overruled by the European ministers. On the deep-sea fisheries, she never took a strong position publicly.</p><p>Even in deciding that the trawling could continue, the European ministers acknowledged the poor state of fish stocks. ‘The scientific advice indicates that most deep-sea stocks are in a precarious situation,’ they said in a statement, and ‘fishing opportunities for those stocks, in order to assure their sustainability, should be reduced.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
Press article, New York Times, Environment page, 3 December 2010<br />
<a href="http://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/03/shrugging-off-criticism-europe-will-keep-trawling/" target="_self">http://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/03/shrugging-off-criticism-europe...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The outcome of the talks on deep-sea fishing quotas shows how complex it is for the EU to deal with strong pressure from member states for keeping the current quotas while respecting its international commitments, such as the adoption of the precautionary approach in fisheries management. This illustrates how difficult the process of the reform of the CFP will be, in particular the external dimension. There is much at stake for ACP countries with the key issue of the compatibility of EU fleets’ access with sustainable ACP fisheries management.</p>
		</div>
		
